COARSENED MATCHING CSDID NOTES

File:
src/matched_estimator_class.py

Scope of the notes below:
- Assume the panel is balanced for all needed variables.
- Assume outcome and matching variables have no missing values.
- Assume first_treat is a valid integer-valued treatment timing column.
- Assume there is at least some treated sample.

Under those assumptions, the main remaining hard-error paths are:

1. No never-treated units in the estimation sample
- _prepare_estimation_data() raises:
  ValueError("No never-treated units in the estimation sample.")

2. Cohort filtering removes all rows
- If cohorts= is passed and nothing survives except an empty sample,
  _prepare_estimation_data() raises:
  ValueError("No data left after cohort restriction.")

3. first_treat is not constant within unit
- If a unit appears with multiple first_treat values across time,
  _prepare_estimation_data() raises:
  ValueError("<n> units have multiple first_treat values.")

4. There are no post-treatment ATT(g,t) cells anywhere
- This is now handled safely.
- Group, calendar, and simple aggregate tables are returned empty
  instead of failing.

5. No cohort has common support after matching
- This is now handled safely.
- fit() can return empty aggregate tables, and event_study_effects
  falls back to the normalized baseline entry instead of failing.

Important non-crashing notes that still matter:

- Existing aggregate outputs already present in the estimator:
  - cohort / group effects
  - event-study effects
  - calendar-time effects
  - simple overall ATT
  - stratum-level pooled effects
  - stratum x event_time pooled effects
- Aggregate selection is controlled at fit-time via the aggregate=
  argument, with "all" as the default.
- Aggregate standard-error selection is controlled at fit-time via the
  se_aggregate= argument, with "all" as the default among the requested
  aggregate outputs.
- se_aggregate cannot include any aggregation that is not also requested
  in aggregate.

- The repository already contains plotting helpers that compute
  stratum-level pooled effects and stratum-by-event-time pooled effects
  from cell_debug_df:
  - src/figures.py -> plot_stratum_aggregated_att()
  - src/figures.py -> plot_stratum_dynamic_effects()

- Those stratum-level summaries are now available as estimator-level
  returned tables.

Important cost note for stratum-level bootstrap standard errors:

- Point-estimate-only versions are cheap.
- Making them full bootstrap-tracked outputs adds extra work on every bootstrap draw:
  grouping and storing results over stratum, and over stratum x event_time.
- The asymptotic dependence on the number of bootstrap draws stays linear,
  but both runtime and especially memory usage increase because the number
  of estimands becomes much larger than the current group/calendar/event/simple
  set.
- The stratum x event_time object is the expensive one: its size grows with
  the number of strata times the number of event times, for every bootstrap draw.

Short version:
- Existing main aggregates are already implemented.
- The remaining hard failures under clean-data assumptions are structural edge cases.
- The estimator now includes stratum-level aggregate tables.
- Bootstrap standard errors are controlled separately via se_aggregate=.
